This is a chronological summary of the major events of the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. The first matches in the group stages of the Football events were played on Wednesday 3 August. The opening ceremony took place on Friday 5 August. The last day of competition and the closing ceremony was on Sunday 21 August. With 306 sets of medals, the games featured 28 Olympic sports, including rugby sevens and golf, which were added to the Olympic program in 2009. These sporting events took place at 33 venues in the host city, and at five in São Paulo, Belo Horizonte, Salvador, Brasília, and Manaus.

Due to the European migrant crisis and other reasons, the International Olympic Committee (IOC) allowed athletes to compete under the Olympic Flag as part of the "Refugee Olympic Team" (ROT); out of 43 refugee athletes deemed potentially eligible, 10 were chosen to form this team.[1] Due to the suspension of the National Olympic Committee of Kuwait, participants from Kuwait were allowed to participate under the Olympic Flag as "Independent Olympic Athletes" (IOA).[2]

Day 0 — Friday 5 August[edit]

5 August 2016 — detailed results
Off-field update
  • Boxer Hassan Saada (Morocco) was arrested over allegations of sexual assault. He was detained for 15 days, pending an investigation, which will prevent him from competing in any boxing events.[5]
Archery
  • The ranking round in both the men's individual competition and the women's individual competition took place.
Opening ceremony
  • The opening ceremony was held at Maracanã Stadium at 20:00 BRT (UTC−3).[6][7] Vanderlei Cordeiro de Lima, marathon bronze medalist at the 2004 Summer Olympics, lit the Olympic cauldron. Soccer legend Pelé, who was widely rumored to be the first choice to light it, was unable to attend for health reasons.[8]

  • Men's 400 m individual medley: Japan's Kosuke Hagino earned the gold medal with a time of 4:06.05, Chase Kalisz of the United States recorded a time of 4:06.75 to win silver, and Japan's Daiya Seto won the bronze with a time of 4:09.71.
  • Women's 400 m individual medley: Hungary's Katinka Hosszú set a world record of 4:26.36 to finish with the gold, the United States's Maya DiRado finished with the silver with a time of 4:31.15, and Spain's Mireia Belmonte recorded 4:32.39 to win the bronze.
  • Women's 4 × 100 m freestyle relay: The Australian team of Emma McKeon, Brittany Elmslie, Bronte Campbell, Cate Campbell set a new world record with a time of 3:30.65 to win gold. Team USA (Simone Manuel, Abbey Weitzeil, Dana Vollmer, Katie Ledecky) finished with silver with a time of 3:31.89 setting a new American record. Team Canada (Sandrine Mainville, Chantal Van Landeghem, Taylor Ruck, Penny Oleksiak) recorded a time of 3:32.89 to win the bronze also setting a new national record.
